{"questionId":"11807","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>This question will explore connections between complex numbers and regular polygons.</p>\n<p>The diagram below shows a sector of a circle of radius 1, with the angle subtended at the centre <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"O\">\n  <mi>O</mi>\n</math></span> being <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\alpha {\\text{,}}\\,\\,0 < \\alpha&nbsp; < \\frac{\\pi }{2}\">\n  <mi>α</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>,</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mn>0</mn>\n  <mo>&lt;</mo>\n  <mi>α</mi>\n  <mo>&lt;</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mi>π</mi>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>. A perpendicular is drawn from point <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"P\">\n  <mi>P</mi>\n</math></span>&nbsp;to intersect the <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span>-axis at <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"Q\">\n  <mi>Q</mi>\n</math></span>. The tangent to the circle at <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"P\">\n  <mi>P</mi>\n</math></span>&nbsp;intersects the <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span>-axis at&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"R\">\n  <mi>R</mi>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/b10eb340b1ebfacbc5106a1f245b6fcc878579ea.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the total area of this <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\"> <mi>n</mi> </math></span> sided polygon.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>Area of&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"O{P_0}{P_1} = \\frac{1}{2}1 \\times 1\\,{\\text{sin}}\\frac{{2\\pi }}{n}\"> <mi>O</mi> <mrow> <msub> <mi>P</mi> <mn>0</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <msub> <mi>P</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mo>×</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mtext>sin</mtext> </mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mi>π</mi> </mrow> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp;so total area is&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{n}{2}{\\text{sin}}\\frac{{2\\pi }}{n}\"> <mfrac> <mi>n</mi> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>sin</mtext> </mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mi>π</mi> </mrow> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> </math></span>.&nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1A1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"11807","referenceCode":"EXM.3.AHL.TZ0.2h","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the total area of this n sided polygon.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"h","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.13—Polar and Euler form"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}